IBM history: From cheese cutter to global flights
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was founded a hundred years ago in New York and initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM only took over in 1924 - originally it was a trademark name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone for the later company IBM laid the fusion of four companies whose history dates back to the 80s of the 19th century.
They owned technologies such as the famous tech card watches to register the start and end of work.
As architect of this new company, Charles Ranlett Flint, who had also chaired the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who appointed the head of the competition company Thomas J. Watson to help him manage the company.
This leader then even put IBM's founders in the shadow - Watson's ideas are based on today's invincible culture and identity of the company.
Watson managed the company until 1952.
IBM, began, as the name already tells us, with the manufacture and distribution of all possible machines for trade - from sausage and cheese cutters, to cashews.
In the first four decades in which Watson led the company, he doubled its sales to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable for the company that he spent the entire forty years in the head chair, but then he was replaced by his son Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, NASA's technicians and computers helped guide NASA's flights into space - Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969, the famous human flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture in 1964 - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC, which determined the computer standard of that time, came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand she bought the consultant part of the PricewaterhouseCooper company and thus entered the business with high added value with consulting services and services.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the last three years is the concept \"Smarter Planet\"
It embodies the intention of using technologies wisely in previously not even planned areas, e.g. to improve the situation in transport and urban administration.
In the trading sector, IBM recently launched the Smart Commerce platform to help traders manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
IBM established a branch office in Czechoslovakia in 1932 - as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe at all.
Today IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central Centre for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague and there is also a world-level research team that deals with the technology of voice recognition.
