Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five approved state travel agencies in the then ČSSR: Čedok, sportsurist, CKM, recrea and autoturist.
The travel agencies sold mainly only trips to the socialist Eastern bloc countries at that time, and in the West only selected ones were allowed to do so.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the peninsula Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania on the Black Sea and to Hungary on the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972 when one was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that it was not even allowed citizens of the Eastern bloc (so also the Czechoslovakians) to travel freely within the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but then one had to buy huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have good acquaintances in the travel office.
That's how things haven't been going for a long time.
The so-called foreign exchange commitment - the condition for a trip to the West - was granted only “politically reliable people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to impose the necessary funds (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the inland, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dazzles - a habit that persists to this day.
The 1989 total revolution followed a travel revolution of the Czechs on foot.
While a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things until 1989, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox, which is no longer known today, is the fact that one could not travel to the most popular country in the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989 at all because it was part of the Yugoslavia at that time.
Right from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the foreign exchange obligation was lifted to neighbouring Western European countries, which created a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
For a long time, the Czechoslovakians were simply unable to get enough of their trips to the West, and everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
For example, the Czech holidaymakers slept in the park while traveling to Paris in the tent, because who had already had the money for an accommodation in the hotel or in a pension?
A typical feature in the foreign travel of Czechs was at that time a suitcase room filled with preserves, beer and permanent sausages, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely interchangeable Czech krone - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the western currency freely.
Our level of life and this also increases average wages, which led to another important moment in 1997.
As a result of increased demand for travel, the travel agencies began to prepare regular trips by charter flights after 1997, which made flight trips incredibly affordable thanks to the possibility of negotiating quantity discounts.
At the end of the 90s, the Czechs, with the exception of the USA, had already had unsolicited payments with all the highly developed countries of the world, which made traveling even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post office travel came in 2000 when, thanks to the high demand of the first direct charter flight to an exotic country, it was completed in Thailand.
Since then, every year direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers fly in distant sunny countries; this year, 12 exotic destinations fly directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 Tsd. Czechs travel annually in exotic countries!
Another significant moment in the era, which marked our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States lifted the visa obligation for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than 15 Tsd. CZK per capita for a single vacation stay.
