In the first year, when Mario López Valdez is in government, unemployment and black labour increased in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
In 2011, the economic history of Sinaloas will be remembered. It is the first year when Mario López Valdez, who described himself as the initiator of change and raised great hopes regarding economic growth, is in government. However, as a result of the climatic contradictions, the main economic indicators did not speak of growth, but, on the contrary, the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused losses in millions of heights in agriculture, but also placed close limits on the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity by 3.6 percent in the first quarter of the year. This mainly accounts for the historical decline in agricultural development by 31.16 percent, which had a negative impact on other economic sectors.
According to a report published by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Susterable (i.e. Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development), 582,000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, 78.03 percent of which were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent were partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity until November has continuously increased unemployment in the Mexican state. Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter of the year because from January to March, 55 053 residents of Sinaloas had no employment, which corresponds to 4.53 per cent of the working population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate increased to 5.28 per cent and from July to September to 6.19 per cent, resulting in 74 000 unemployed people in Sinaloa. These are 18 969 more than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
The unemployment rate in Sinaloa in the year relies on several factors. Economic scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, dean of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), commented that the policies of public institutions indirectly explain the growing unemployment.
\"What we are currently observing is an increase in unemployment, which has several factors to do with, among other things, liquidity losses in the market due to the cuts in the legislation adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who accumulate prohibited dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves to invest them or use them for anything else,\" he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
\"The number of persons leaving the country looking for work abroad, especially in the United States, has fallen. On the one hand, this is due to the entry problems and on the other hand, because it is difficult to find work there.
Black Paper
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious if one takes into account the high proportion of black labour, which, according to INEGI, comprises 60.38 percent of those employed in the country who work without paying in the cashiers of social insurance.
The low wages, the lowest in all of Mexico, come to unemployment and black labour, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Insurance Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government of Labour and Social Care in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 Pesos by September, which is much less than the general government average, which is 7375 Pesos.
