He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, of which a part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low one - the so-called malthenes. Together, they give the street covering its characteristic tehelastic behaviour.
Tähelastic behaviour of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very tough and almost solid at 50°C, while it breaks at very low temperatures.
“This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes one day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations,” the chemical engineer performed.
The researcher of the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City had mostly a flexible street floor, composed of six layers of material, of which the last three included asphalt.
Between the top layers lay a layer of asphalt, which consisted of small, asphalt-baked stones and then solidified stones.
Each single stone of this layer of wear has been bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles are moved and forces are generated on it, this layer allows for a good distribution of forces in the street floor.
“If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed,” said the chemical engineer.
\"On the layer of wear, he carried out, \"a last layer is being designed, the so-called carrying layer, consisting of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they need to produce friction.
The most forces received and distributed by this street floor also requires an adequate thickness and the material from which it consists must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, especially the water - he said - since it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain is moistened, water enters the layer and is only difficult to recover. This causes a wave of all layers of the street floor and as a result the occurrence of blowholes.
